data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert count explicitly
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all items match a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 7"* instead of just *"Expected: True, Actual: False"*
- **Add message strings** to `Assert.IsTrue` — otherwise failures are opaque
- **`users.Any()`** over `users.Single()` — `Single` throws its own exception, masking the test failure
- **`CollectionAssert`** is useful for comparing two lists:

```csharp
// Check exact contents (order-insensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);

// Check exact contents + order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Check all items are a specific type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Check no nulls
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

// Check a collection contains a specific item
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
```

**Rule of thumb:** prefer the most specific assert — it produces the most useful failure message.
